snippet.textDisplay:
Why does everyone think climate change is all about greenhouse gasses? That's only a small part of it. The bigger cause of climate change is deforestation and the elimination of plants as we take up more and more land, then we also cover bodies of water with floating plastic and crap that prevents the water cycle from working properly.

Imagine how much less water can evaporate because we trap them in containers, in our trash, bury it underground, fracking, etc. Imagine a radiator that you restricted the flow of coolant or decreased the surface area by shrinking the radiator.

Plants are basically smart radiators for the planet. They help keep the planet cool with evaporative cooling, shade, and by pulling the water up from the ground so it can evaporate easier for rain to prevent drought. They feed us and provide housing for other animals. They take in CO2, the greenhouse gas, and put out oxygen. As it gets cooler, they drop their leaves to allow the sunlight to reach further, but at the same time the leaves act as insulation to the planet and keep the water from evaporating, basically like putting a lid on a pot. People need to do better studies on that and stop pushing just CO2 emission reduction, but to find ways to relocate plants that we remove so that we don't lose all the benefits they provide.

snippet.textDisplay:
I'm a bit surprised this wasn't more in the MKBHD arena. To be totally honest, many other interview exist of Bill Gates that are around the topics seen in this interview but are done in a much more educated, deep dive way. Or, there are a million little surface interviews like this from a million different people. This is Bill Gates, this quick surface back n forth has to literally be out there in the 1000's.
What I want to see from an MKBHD interview are questions around tech and what Bill likes to use when it comes to tech. A few silly surface lightning round questions would be cool. Android or iPhone? Regular bicycle or electric bicycle? NY or LA? Cable TV or streaming? etc.. A bunch of those would be neat. But then the real questions. Does your home PC have a custom version of Windows? How much of your own feedback goes into the Windows platform? You had a beautiful, high tech home built a certain number of years ago, how does that compare with the modern smart home devices of today? Have you added to it since you built your custom smart home? Do you cover your laptop camera with black tape? When he mentioned his Porsche E-Vehicle I totally thought Marques would do a deeper dive into that. Have you driven a Tesla? How do you like the Porsche in comparison? Do you miss Autopilot? Does Porsche have anything similar? What's the fastest you've driven it? Are there any other cool, big purchase toys you can tell us about? Do you ever take a break and just go to a race track or go on a vacation? What is your favorite piece of tech over the years, what little device stands out the most to you? What did you think of the first iPhone? Do you ever regret not taking a stronger path into the smartphone OS market?
This is all off the top of my head but you get what I mean. I don't click on an MKBHD interview to hear a brief summary of what that person is doing. I know these are usually pretty short, so real researched questions can't really be expected, there isn't enough time. With the limited time it should be more about favorite tech and how their life relates to tech. How they've influenced tech or how tech has influenced them. I'd like to see much more fun questions here.
IDK... that's my opinion, but I think it makes sense. Hope you have a chance to read this and consider.
Thanks! And otherwise great job. Glad you're doing these. Keep killin it👍

snippet.textDisplay:
Gates comments on range anxiety are really disappointing....my 2012 Honda civic has a range of about 320 miles in the city....the Tesla has a range of 390....wtf is he talking about? Clearly has no clue...Porsche probably gave him the car for free...that's why he plugged it. (Apple sends free iPhones to all the fortune 100 CEOs...it's good advertising....same bs)


The new Tesla Roadster is supposed to have over 500 mile range coming out in a year....


If he's talking about long distance driving....I don't know about anyone else but when I'm driving, I usually need to stop every 3-4 hours (about 200 miles) for a stretch, some food and bathroom. So if I drive 200 miles in a Model S, that means I've only used half my range. With the new super charging stations you can charge 50% battery in 20 minutes. Unless you're by yourself or are running a fire drill, it takes up to 20 minutes to get a typical family out of a car, into the bathrooms and back...that's without standing in line for ordering food at the rest stop fast food restaurants, etc.


Worst case scenario you have to chill in the car and catch up on netflix or youtube videos for 10 minutes...


It's really a shame because people are going to listen to Gates and think range is still an actual problem for electric vehicles, whereas in fact EVs are out competing their fossil fuel competitors in every way....including range.


In 5 years range discussions of fossil fuel vs. EVs will be equivalent to chess discussions of human vs. computers/AI....EVs and AI will win everytime.
